00:45:56.910 --> 00:45:58.430
a lot with that on the show.

00:45:58.430 --> 00:45:59.596
INTERVIEWER: I figured that.

00:45:59.596 --> 00:46:00.360
TY FRANCK: Yeah.

00:46:00.360 --> 00:46:03.320
They've asked for my opinion
on a great many of those things

00:46:03.320 --> 00:46:06.070
and seem to be taking it
seriously, so that's very cool.

00:46:06.070 --> 00:46:08.250
DANIEL ABRAHAM: And the
amount of participation

00:46:08.250 --> 00:46:10.670
we've gotten to
have in the process

00:46:10.670 --> 00:46:14.870
is as far as I can
tell, unprecedented.

00:46:14.870 --> 00:46:16.940
We've actually been
in the writer's room

00:46:16.940 --> 00:46:21.020
and talking with the show
runners for almost two months

00:46:21.020 --> 00:46:23.240
now.

00:46:23.240 --> 00:46:28.250
And that's a terrible plan.

00:46:28.250 --> 00:46:31.630
I mean, writers are
cranky, antisocial people.

00:46:31.630 --> 00:46:37.210
And putting them in the middle
of this really complicated

00:46:37.210 --> 00:46:39.940
social negotiation,
generally speaking,

00:46:39.940 --> 00:46:41.410
I would recommend against it.

00:46:41.410 --> 00:46:43.030
It's worked out well for us.

00:46:43.030 --> 00:46:48.560
But as a result, we've gotten to
be there for a lot of the work

00:46:48.560 --> 00:46:53.590
that they've done on how to
take the text and take the story

00:46:53.590 --> 00:46:56.590
and reimagine it for
a different medium

00:46:56.590 --> 00:46:58.690
and for the requirements
of that medium.

00:46:58.690 --> 00:46:59.950
That's been a really cool.

00:47:04.790 --> 00:47:07.830
AUDIENCE: Dovetailing on
this, I have a pet theory

00:47:07.830 --> 00:47:11.760
that really iconic stories
come out of changes in medium,

00:47:11.760 --> 00:47:14.830
like what persists
through all the mediums

00:47:14.830 --> 00:47:19.180
is like the stuff that
will persist a long way.

00:47:19.180 --> 00:47:20.540
And so I was kind of curious.

00:47:20.540 --> 00:47:23.680
It sounds like this actually
started as an MMORPG,

00:47:23.680 --> 00:47:26.000
then it went to table
top, then became a novel,

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:28.710
and is now going to
TV, which is the most

00:47:28.710 --> 00:47:30.604
medium hops I've ever heard.

00:47:30.604 --> 00:47:32.687
So I was wondering if you
could tell us about some

00:47:32.687 --> 00:47:36.040
of the early media hops,
and like what was retained

00:47:36.040 --> 00:47:39.864
and what dropped, and
where new things came in.

00:47:39.864 --> 00:47:41.530
DANIEL ABRAHAM: I can
only get into that

00:47:41.530 --> 00:47:43.738
when you start going from
table top to novels, so I--

00:47:43.738 --> 00:47:45.780
TY FRANCK: Yeah.

00:47:45.780 --> 00:47:49.560
We didn't get too far in
the MMO, other than just

00:47:49.560 --> 00:47:52.360
sort of the world building.

00:47:52.360 --> 00:47:56.410
When I start running it as an
MM-- or as a tabletop game,

00:47:56.410 --> 00:47:59.750
I had to obviously
find some rules.

00:47:59.750 --> 00:48:03.430
In that case, I wound up using
the open source d20 Modern

00:48:03.430 --> 00:48:06.150
rules as sort of
the skeleton for it

00:48:06.150 --> 00:48:08.650
and then made up all
my own space rules,

00:48:08.650 --> 00:48:12.300
because the d20 future
rules are stupid.

00:48:12.300 --> 00:48:14.100
That was the big shift there.

00:48:14.100 --> 00:48:15.920
And there wasn't
really a story yet.

00:48:15.920 --> 00:48:18.380
So I didn't have to change
anything story-wise.

00:48:18.380 --> 00:48:21.650
It was actually in coming
up with what the events were

00:48:21.650 --> 00:48:24.050
for the tabletop
game that actually

00:48:24.050 --> 00:48:26.300
started creating story.

00:48:26.300 --> 00:48:30.480
And then when Daniel wanted
to turn it into a novel,

00:48:30.480 --> 00:48:32.480
that it is evolved greatly.

00:48:32.480 --> 00:48:37.300
Because the things that work
in games don't work in novels,

00:48:37.300 --> 00:48:39.220
or it's not 100%.

00:48:39.220 --> 00:48:41.747
There's a little sliver on that
Venn diagram where it works.

00:48:41.747 --> 00:48:43.580
So you drop all the
stuff that doesn't work.

00:48:43.580 --> 00:48:47.330
You add a bunch of
stuff that does work.

00:48:47.330 --> 00:48:52.092
We're not going to game Miller
being sad in his apartment.

00:48:52.092 --> 00:48:54.300
DANIEL ABRAHAM: A chapter
of my character sits there.

00:48:54.300 --> 00:48:55.070
TY FRANCK: Yeah.

00:48:55.070 --> 00:48:56.005
And drinks and is sad.

00:48:56.005 --> 00:48:57.880
DANIEL ABRAHAM: Role
your disconsolate rogue.

00:48:57.880 --> 00:48:59.190
TY FRANCK: Yeah, right.

00:48:59.190 --> 00:49:00.370
DANIEL ABRAHAM: You
are disconsolate.

00:49:00.370 --> 00:49:01.411
TY FRANCK: Yeah, exactly.

00:49:01.411 --> 00:49:03.730
That's not going to work.

00:49:03.730 --> 00:49:06.680
And then now between
novel and TV,

00:49:06.680 --> 00:49:08.890
You're seeing the
same sorts of things.

00:49:08.890 --> 00:49:10.946
Again, in the novel,
it works to have

00:49:10.946 --> 00:49:12.570
Miller sit in his
apartment and be sad.

00:49:12.570 --> 00:49:13.944
Because we're
inside of his head.

00:49:13.944 --> 00:49:16.540
And we get to see all the
interesting internal dialogue

00:49:16.540 --> 00:49:17.589
he's having.

00:49:17.589 --> 00:49:19.130
That would be a
really boring episode

00:49:19.130 --> 00:49:22.200
of TV, 42 minutes of Detective
Miller drinking scotch

00:49:22.200 --> 00:49:24.260
in his apartment and being sad.

00:49:24.260 --> 00:49:27.720
So now we're looking for ways,
how do you visually dramatize

00:49:27.720 --> 00:49:30.920
that you've got a guy who's sad.

00:49:30.920 --> 00:49:34.990
And it's interesting
watching that transition.

00:49:34.990 --> 00:49:40.120
DANIEL ABRAHAM: And to go
to your theory, the model

00:49:40.120 --> 00:49:42.390
that I have for
this is translation.

00:49:42.390 --> 00:49:44.009
And I know only one language.

00:49:44.009 --> 00:49:45.550
So all of my knowledge
or translation

00:49:45.550 --> 00:49:47.133
comes from reading
Douglas Hofstadter.

00:49:49.410 --> 00:49:53.100
But the idea of
changing the obstacles

00:49:53.100 --> 00:49:55.140
that you have in
telling the story

00:49:55.140 --> 00:49:58.060
changes the form of the story.

00:49:58.060 --> 00:50:00.160
And it can be related.

00:50:00.160 --> 00:50:01.430
And it can be very close.

00:50:01.430 --> 00:50:04.070
Or it could be more
general what level

00:50:04.070 --> 00:50:06.290
you're trying to translate
on whether you're

00:50:06.290 --> 00:50:09.480
trying to translate the exact
words, or the exact actions,

00:50:09.480 --> 00:50:12.050
or the effect that
those actions have,

00:50:12.050 --> 00:50:15.270
or different sets of
solutions to the problem.

00:50:15.270 --> 00:50:17.080
And so yeah,
intellectually, it's

00:50:17.080 --> 00:50:19.030
just a fascinating
bunch of problems.

00:50:19.030 --> 00:50:20.290
And it's really cool.

00:50:20.290 --> 00:50:22.580
INTERVIEWER: Ty,
Daniel, thank you

00:50:22.580 --> 00:50:24.744
for coming and
talking with us, and--

00:50:24.744 --> 00:50:26.410
DANIEL ABRAHAM: Thank
you for having us.

00:50:26.410 --> 00:50:28.338
TY FRANCK: Thank you.

00:50:28.338 --> 00:50:32.962
[APPLAUSE]

